## Empirical Evidence: Suicide Terrorism Case Studies

Suicide terrorism, a particularly lethal form, has been extensively studied to understand motivations:

| Factor Category        | Key Findings                                                                                          | Representative Studies                                  |
|-----------------------|-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|--------------------------------------------------------|
| Individual-level       | Trauma, identity fusion, quest for personal significance, altruism                                  | Pedahzur et al. (2003), Kruglanski et al. (2009)       |
| Organizational-level  | Strategic use against hardened targets, leadership influence, recruitment dynamics                   | Pape (2003), Gambetta (2005), Moghadam (2003)          |
| Societal-level        | Cultural norms supporting martyrdom, community support, political oppression                        | Burdman (2003), Khashan (2003), Ramasubramanian (2004) |

Suicide terrorists are often motivated by a complex interplay of personal, organizational, and societal factors rather than a single cause ([Harmon et al., 2018](https://www.hsaj.org/articles/14749)).

